# Tools for building and combining `task`s -- asynchronous computations
# that run on Pluma's single-threaded event loop.
#
# The `task` type itself is built in and always available (see the
# prelude), and this module is auto-imported like `option`/`result`, so
# `task.return`, `task.sleep`, and friends resolve with no `use` line.
#
# You rarely call `task.then` by hand: inside a function that returns a
# `task`, `try x = some-task` awaits it and reads top-to-bottom, the same
# way `try` works over `option`/`result`. The combinators here
# (`task.all`, `task.race`, `task.with-timeout`, â€¦) compose tasks that run
# concurrently; `scope` (a keyword) is the structured-concurrency block
# they're built on. See ASYNC.md.

# Lifts a plain value into a task that is already finished. `task.return
# 5` is the task that immediately produces `5`. It's how an async function
# hands back its final result:
#
#     try user = http.get url
#     task.return user.name
public def return :: fun a -> task a = built-in "task-return"

# A task that fails with `e` the moment it runs. Failure propagates
# through `try` (the awaiting task fails too) until something recovers it
# with `??` / `task.or-else` or reifies it with `task.attempt`. The error
# value is untyped from the task's point of view -- `task a` tracks only
# the success type.
public def fail :: fun e -> task a = built-in "task-fail"

# Hands the scheduler a turn without doing any I/O. A long CPU-bound loop
# can call `task.yield ()` periodically so sibling tasks (and cancellation)
# get a chance to run -- tasks are cooperatively scheduled, so nothing
# else proceeds until the running task suspends.
public def yield :: fun nothing -> task nothing = built-in "task-yield"

# A task that completes after `d` elapses, producing nothing. Suspends the
# task on a timer rather than blocking the thread, so siblings keep
# running. `try _ = task.sleep 200ms` pauses just the current task.
public def sleep :: fun duration -> task nothing = built-in "task-sleep"

# Chains a follow-up step onto a task: `then t k` runs `t`, and when it
# succeeds runs `k` on the result (which returns the next task). If `t`
# fails, `k` is skipped and the failure propagates. This is the explicit
# form of what `try` does line-by-line, so reach for `try` instead unless
# you're building a combinator:
#
#     try x = t
#     k x
public def then :: fun (task a) (fun a -> task b) -> task b = built-in "task-then"

# Recovers from a failed task. `or-else t recover` runs `t`; if it succeeds,
# its value passes through, and `recover` is never run. If `t` fails,
# `recover` runs and *its* task is used instead. This is exactly what `??`
# does over a task, so you'll usually write the operator:
#
#     fetch-primary () ?? fetch-backup ()
public def or-else :: fun (task a) (fun nothing -> task a) -> task a = built-in "task-or-else"

# Reifies a task's failure into its value. `attempt t` runs `t` and always
# succeeds: `ok v` if `t` produced `v`, `err e` if `t` failed with `e`. This
# is how you keep going past a failure -- a failed `attempt`ed task no longer
# fails its scope, so `task.all (list.map ts task.attempt)` settles every
# task instead of stopping at the first error.
public def attempt :: fun (task a) -> task (result a e) = built-in "task-attempt"

# Transforms a task's successful value with a plain function. `map t f` runs
# `t` and applies `f` to its result; a failure passes through untouched. Note
# the task-first argument order (like the other combinators here, and so it
# composes with `|`):
#
#     http.get url | task.map parse-body
public def map :: fun (task a) (fun a -> b) -> task b = built-in "task-map"
